    content: "Conjunctivitis is inflammation of the conjunctiva: the thin, transparent mucous membrane covering the anterior sclera (bulbar conjunctiva) and lining the inner eyelids (palpebral conjunctiva). The conjunctiva contains goblet cells that secrete mucin for the tear film, immune cells (lymphocytes, mast cells, dendritic cells) that provide local defense, and a rich vascular network that dilates during inflammation, producing the characteristic conjunctival injection (red eye). The pathophysiology varies by etiology: bacterial, viral, and allergic conjunctivitis each involve distinct molecular pathways that produce characteristic clinical presentations important for differentiation and appropriate management.\n\nBacterial conjunctivitis is most commonly caused by Staphylococcus aureus, Streptococcus pneumoniae, Haemophilus influenzae, and Moraxella catarrhalis. Bacteria adhere to conjunctival epithelial cells via pili and adhesins, triggering innate immune activation through Toll-like receptor (TLR) recognition of pathogen-associated molecular patterns (PAMPs). Neutrophils are recruited via IL-8 and other chemokines, producing purulent discharge rich in dead neutrophils, bacteria, and cellular debris. Gonococcal conjunctivitis (Neisseria gonorrhoeae) is a hyperacute form that produces copious purulent discharge and can penetrate intact corneal epithelium, causing corneal perforation if untreated. Viral conjunctivitis is most commonly caused by adenovirus (serotypes 8, 19, 37 for epidemic keratoconjunctivitis), which infects conjunctival epithelial cells, triggering a predominantly lymphocytic/mononuclear immune response with watery discharge, follicular reaction on the palpebral conjunctiva, and preauricular lymphadenopathy.\n\nAllergic conjunctivitis is a type I hypersensitivity reaction (IgE-mediated) triggered by allergens such as pollen, dust mites, or animal dander. Allergens cross-link IgE antibodies on conjunctival mast cell surfaces, causing mast cell degranulation and release of preformed mediators (histamine, tryptase) and newly synthesized mediators (leukotrienes, prostaglandins). Histamine acts on H1 receptors on conjunctival blood vessels causing vasodilation and increased permeability (redness and chemosis), on sensory nerve endings causing intense itching (the hallmark symptom), and on goblet cells increasing mucus production. Seasonal allergic conjunctivitis recurs with pollen exposure, while perennial allergic conjunctivitis persists year-round from indoor allergens."
