    content: "Ophthalmic anti-inflammatory medications target the arachidonic acid cascade and immune-mediated inflammation in ocular tissues. Corticosteroids (prednisolone acetate, dexamethasone, loteprednol) are the most potent ophthalmic anti-inflammatory agents, acting by binding to intracellular glucocorticoid receptors, translocating to the nucleus, and modifying gene transcription. They upregulate anti-inflammatory proteins (lipocortin-1/annexin A1, which inhibits phospholipase A2) and downregulate pro-inflammatory mediators (COX-2, iNOS, cytokines including TNF-α, IL-1β, IL-6, and adhesion molecules like ICAM-1). By inhibiting phospholipase A2, corticosteroids prevent the release of arachidonic acid from cell membrane phospholipids, blocking the entire downstream cascade of both prostaglandins (via COX pathway) and leukotrienes (via lipoxygenase pathway).\n\nOphthalmic NSAIDs (ketorolac, nepafenac, diclofenac, bromfenac) selectively inhibit cyclooxygenase (COX) enzymes without affecting the lipoxygenase pathway, making them less potent anti-inflammatory agents than corticosteroids but with a significantly better safety profile. COX-1 and COX-2 convert arachidonic acid to prostaglandin H2, which is then converted to tissue-specific prostaglandins (PGE2, PGF2α, PGI2) and thromboxane A2. In the eye, prostaglandins are key mediators of the inflammatory response following surgery, trauma, or infection: they cause miosis, blood-aqueous barrier breakdown (with protein leakage into the aqueous humor), vasodilation, increased vascular permeability, and pain sensitization. Nepafenac is a prodrug that penetrates the cornea efficiently and is converted to its active metabolite amfenac by intraocular esterases, achieving high drug concentrations at the retina.\n\nThe clinical choice between steroids and NSAIDs depends on the severity and type of inflammation. Post-surgical inflammation typically requires corticosteroids (prednisolone acetate tapered over 4-6 weeks) to control the blood-aqueous barrier breakdown and prevent posterior synechiae formation. NSAIDs are used adjunctively to manage pain and prevent cystoid macular edema (CME): a common cause of suboptimal visual recovery after cataract surgery caused by prostaglandin-mediated breakdown of the perifoveal capillary blood-retinal barrier. Steroid side effects: particularly elevated IOP (steroid-response glaucoma caused by increased trabecular meshwork outflow resistance from glycosaminoglycan accumulation) and posterior subcapsular cataract formation: limit the duration and intensity of corticosteroid therapy."
