    content: "Osmotic agents are hyperosmolar substances administered intravenously (mannitol) or orally (glycerin, isosorbide) to create a transient blood-ocular osmotic gradient that rapidly draws water out of the eye, reducing vitreous volume and acutely lowering intraocular pressure. These agents are primarily used in ophthalmic emergencies such as acute angle-closure crisis, where IOP may exceed 60-70 mmHg and must be reduced rapidly to prevent ischemic optic nerve damage. The mechanism relies on the principle that the blood-aqueous and blood-vitreous barriers are relatively impermeable to these large solute molecules, so when plasma osmolarity is acutely elevated by the osmotic agent, water moves along the osmotic gradient from the intraocular compartments (aqueous humor and vitreous body) into the hyperosmolar bloodstream.\n\nMannitol is a sugar alcohol (C6H14O6) that is freely filtered at the glomerulus but not reabsorbed, acting as an osmotic diuretic. When administered intravenously (1-2 g/kg over 30-60 minutes), it rapidly increases serum osmolarity by 20-40 mOsm/kg, creating a powerful osmotic gradient that extracts water from the vitreous cavity (which is ~99% water). IOP reduction begins within 30-60 minutes and lasts 4-6 hours. The IOP-lowering effect is most pronounced when the blood-ocular barrier is intact: inflammation or neovascularization that disrupts these barriers allows mannitol to enter the eye, reducing the osmotic gradient and potentially causing a paradoxical rebound IOP increase as the drug equilibrates.\n\nOral glycerin (glycerol) is an alternative osmotic agent that can be given orally (1-1.5 g/kg mixed with juice). It is absorbed from the GI tract, raises serum osmolarity, and produces similar IOP-lowering effects within 30-60 minutes. However, glycerin is metabolized and provides 4.3 kcal/g, causing significant hyperglycemia in diabetic clients: making isosorbide (a non-caloric osmotic agent) the preferred oral option for diabetic clients. Both oral agents may cause nausea and vomiting due to their hyperosmolar effect on the GI tract. The primary complications of osmotic agents are related to their potent diuretic effect: dehydration, electrolyte imbalances (particularly hyponatremia), and fluid overload in clients with compromised cardiac or renal function (as intravascular volume initially expands before diuresis begins)."
