    content: "Otitis media is an inflammatory condition of the middle ear space (the air-filled cavity between the tympanic membrane and the inner ear) most commonly resulting from eustachian tube dysfunction and secondary bacterial infection. The eustachian tube connects the middle ear to the nasopharynx and serves three critical functions: ventilation (equalizing middle ear pressure with atmospheric pressure), drainage (clearing mucus and secretions from the middle ear), and protection (preventing nasopharyngeal secretions from entering the middle ear). In children, the eustachian tube is shorter (18 mm vs 36 mm in adults), more horizontal (10° angle vs 45° in adults), and has less developed cartilaginous support, all of which impair its opening mechanism and predispose to middle ear effusion and infection.\n\nAcute otitis media (AOM) typically begins with a viral upper respiratory infection that causes inflammation and edema of the nasopharyngeal mucosa and eustachian tube epithelium. Eustachian tube swelling impairs ventilation and drainage, creating negative pressure in the middle ear that draws nasopharyngeal secretions (along with bacteria) retrograde into the middle ear space. The warm, moist, nutrient-rich middle ear environment promotes bacterial proliferation: most commonly Streptococcus pneumoniae, non-typeable Haemophilus influenzae, and Moraxella catarrhalis. Bacterial virulence factors (pneumolysin, IgA protease, biofilm formation) overwhelm local mucosal immune defenses, triggering neutrophil recruitment, inflammatory cytokine release (IL-1, IL-6, TNF-α), and purulent effusion formation. The accumulated pressure from pus within the non-expandable middle ear space causes the characteristic severe ear pain (otalgia) and can lead to tympanic membrane bulging and eventual perforation.\n\nOtitis media with effusion (OME) refers to fluid in the middle ear without signs of acute infection: the effusion may persist for weeks to months after AOM or develop insidiously from chronic eustachian tube dysfunction. Chronic or recurrent OME causes conductive hearing loss due to the fluid mass dampening tympanic membrane and ossicular chain vibration, which is particularly concerning in young children during critical speech and language development periods. Complications of untreated AOM include tympanic membrane perforation, mastoiditis (infection spreading to the mastoid air cells), cholesteatoma formation, labyrinthitis (inner ear involvement causing vertigo and sensorineural hearing loss), and rarely, intracranial complications such as meningitis, brain abscess, or lateral sinus thrombosis."
