    content: "Ménière's disease is a chronic inner ear disorder characterized by the classic triad (tetrad) of episodic vertigo, fluctuating sensorineural hearing loss, tinnitus, and aural fullness, resulting from endolymphatic hydrops: an abnormal accumulation of endolymph within the membranous labyrinth of the inner ear. The inner ear contains two fluid-filled compartments: the endolymphatic space (filled with endolymph: high potassium, low sodium, similar to intracellular fluid) and the perilymphatic space (filled with perilymph: high sodium, low potassium, similar to extracellular fluid). The stria vascularis in the cochlea actively secretes potassium into the endolymph, maintaining the critical +80 mV endocochlear potential that drives mechanotransduction in hair cells. Endolymph is reabsorbed by the endolymphatic sac through mechanisms involving aquaporin water channels and sodium transporters.\n\nIn Ménière's disease, either overproduction or impaired reabsorption of endolymph (or both) causes progressive distension of the endolymphatic space. The exact etiology remains unclear but likely involves multifactorial contributions: autoimmune injury to the endolymphatic sac, viral-mediated inflammation (HSV, CMV), anatomical variations reducing endolymphatic sac capacity, genetic predisposition (familial clustering in ~10% of cases), and altered endolymph ion homeostasis. As endolymph volume increases, the thin Reissner's membrane (separating the endolymphatic scala media from the perilymphatic scala vestibuli) distends and eventually ruptures. Membrane rupture allows potassium-rich endolymph to mix with sodium-rich perilymph, creating a toxic ionic environment that depolarizes and paralyzes vestibular hair cells and cochlear hair cells.\n\nThis endolymph-perilymph mixing produces the acute Ménière's attack: sudden vestibular hair cell depolarization causes intense rotational vertigo lasting 20 minutes to several hours, accompanied by nausea, vomiting, and nystagmus. Cochlear hair cell toxicity causes acute sensorineural hearing loss (initially low-frequency, reversible) and tinnitus. Between attacks, the Reissner's membrane heals and endolymph composition normalizes, but repeated episodes cause cumulative hair cell damage, progressive permanent hearing loss (eventually affecting all frequencies), and chronic vestibular dysfunction. The disease typically affects one ear initially but becomes bilateral in approximately 30-50% of cases over time. Drop attacks (Tumarkin otolithic crisis): sudden falls without loss of consciousness from acute otolith organ stimulation: are a dangerous manifestation in advanced disease."
