    content: "Hearing loss is classified into three categories based on the anatomical location of dysfunction: conductive (external/middle ear), sensorineural (inner ear/cochlear nerve), and mixed (combined). Understanding the physiology of normal hearing is essential for comprehending how each type disrupts sound processing. Sound waves enter the external auditory canal and vibrate the tympanic membrane, which transmits mechanical energy through the ossicular chain (malleus, incus, stapes) to the oval window of the cochlea. The ossicular chain amplifies sound pressure approximately 22-fold through a lever action and the area ratio between the large tympanic membrane and the small stapes footplate, compensating for the impedance mismatch between air and the fluid-filled cochlea.\n\nConductive hearing loss results from any condition that impairs sound transmission through the external or middle ear to the cochlea. Common causes include cerumen impaction (physically blocks sound wave transmission), otitis media with effusion (fluid mass dampens tympanic membrane and ossicular vibration), tympanic membrane perforation (reduces effective vibrating surface area), otosclerosis (abnormal bone remodeling fixates the stapes footplate in the oval window, preventing ossicular chain vibration), and cholesteatoma (destructive keratinized epithelial growth erodes ossicles). Conductive loss is often correctable through medical or surgical intervention because the inner ear sensorineural apparatus remains intact.\n\nSensorineural hearing loss (SNHL) results from damage to the cochlear hair cells, the stria vascularis, or the cochlear nerve (CN VIII). In the cochlea, inner hair cells (IHCs, ~3,500) are the primary sensory transducers that convert mechanical vibration into electrical signals via mechanotransduction: displacement of stereocilia opens tip-link-connected mechanoelectrical transduction (MET) channels, allowing potassium influx from the endolymph, depolarizing the hair cell and triggering neurotransmitter (glutamate) release onto spiral ganglion neurons. Outer hair cells (OHCs, ~12,000) act as cochlear amplifiers through electromotility: prestin proteins in their lateral membrane contract and elongate in response to membrane potential changes, mechanically amplifying basilar membrane vibration and enhancing frequency selectivity. OHC loss reduces cochlear amplification by 40-60 dB and impairs frequency discrimination. Causes of SNHL include presbycusis (age-related cumulative loss of hair cells and strial atrophy), noise-induced hearing loss (excessive acoustic energy causes metabolic exhaustion, reactive oxygen species generation, and mechanical destruction of hair cells), ototoxic medications (aminoglycosides, cisplatin, loop diuretics damage OHCs through mitochondrial apoptosis), and acoustic neuroma (vestibular schwannoma compressing CN VIII)."
